 NEW DELHI, Aug 7 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - Scores of Hindu pilgrims went on a rampage near the Indian capital on Tuesday, setting buses on fire and blocking a highway after two of them were run over and killed by a truck, police said. No one was injured in the violent protests which took place on the road which connects New Delhi to the northwestern tourist city of Jaipur. "The traffic is now moving. We had to resort to minor caning to disperse the crowd," senior police officer Satish Balan said, adding that two buses were burned and two police vehicles damaged by the mob. The pilgrims, who worship Hindu god Shiva, walk hundreds of miles every year to collect holy water from rivers in northern India and also visit temples across the region. They are notorious for their temper and are known to turn violent if traffic is not stopped to allow them cross roads or if they get hit by a vehicle. Television footage showed pligrims, many of them dressed in traditional saffron-coloured shirts, shouting angry slogans and blocking traffic at Manesar, an industrial hub near New Delhi. One bus was on fire while smoke bellowed from another. Some protesters were shown breaking windscreens of vehicles with what appeared to be iron ro
